07640nam a22011655i 9783110197372DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082005gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)948655881  a97831101973727 a10.1515/97831101973722doi  a(DE-B1597)32208  a(OCoLC)853255295  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP118.2b.I583 2005eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a418/.0071222  aER 9252rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27775:00aInvestigations in Instructed Second Language Acquisition /ced. by Alex Housen, Michel Pierrard. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (568 p.) :bFigs. and tabs.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies on Language Acquisition [SOLA] ,x1861-4248 ;v250 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMethods in current instructed second language acquisition research range from laboratory experiments to ethnography using non-obtrusive participant observation, from cross-sectional designs to longitudinal case studies. Many different types of data serve as the basis for analysis, including reaction times measurements, global test scores, paper and pencil measures, introspective comments, grammaticality judgements, as well as textual data (elicited or naturalistic, oral or written, relating to comprehension or production). Some studies rely on extensive quantification of data, while others may favour a more qualitative and hermeneutic analytic approach. Many of these issues and methods are exemplified by the contributions to this volume. Data-based studies included here deal with the acquisition of specific linguistic phenomena (e.g. verb and noun morphology, lexicon, clause structures) in a range of target languages (e.g. English, French, German, Russian) from a variety of settings involving different instructional approaches (e.g. traditional foreign language classes, immersion classes, intensive ESL classes, content and language integrated language classes). Collectively, the chapters in this book illustrate the productivity and diversity of current research on instructed second language acquisition. As such they serve as a valuable resource for researchers in SLA, psycholinguistics, linguistics, and language education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aSecond language acquisition. 4aGermanische Sprachen. 4aSpracherwerb. 4aZweitspracherwerbsforschung. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aAmmar, Ahlem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChernigovskaya, Tatiana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewaele, Jean-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGor, Kira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGriggs, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHousen, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHousen, Alex, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoward, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJärvinen, Heini-Marja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKida, Tsuyoshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuiken, Folkert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaufer, Batia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLightbown, Patsy M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLochtman, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenzel, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary